    <prp:abstract>Our goal is to reveal the magnetic field influence on the protoplanetary disk TW Hya. For this purpose, we propose to use the unique angular resolution and sensitivity of ALMA in full polarization mode in band 6. We will measure the magnetic field strength and structure by imaging the linearly polarized continuum emission of TW Hya with unprecedented sensitivity of 0.3% polarization at a 3 sigma level and spatial resolution of 0.19". By this, we will resolve full polarization in the closest and brightest analog of the solar nebula. This will be the first image of the spatially resolved magnetic field of TW Hya uncovering direct constraints on magnetic field properties in protoplanetary disks. In conjunction to the observations, the data will be analyzed by fitting the polarization maps using a combination of 3D MHD + RT modeling of the thermal reemission by aligned, non-spherical dust grains. We will constrain the grain alignment processes along with the dust grain asphericity, even non-detections will provide stringent limits, and will help assess turbulent mechanisms responsible for retarding the grain alignment. </prp:abstract>
